6. Cascading Dropdown in Power Apps?

EXPLAIN IN ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ Cascading dropdowns are filter the options in one dropdown depend on the selection made in another dropdown.
For Example: 
ðŸ‘‰ We have a two dropdowns one is country another is state.
ðŸ‘‰ When a user selects a country in the first dropdown, the second dropdown shows only states from that country.
Dropdown 1 (Country) ---> Items property: Distinct(CountriesCities, Country)
Dropdown 2 (state)   ---> Items property: Filter(CountriesCities, Country = Dropdown1.Selected.Result)

Example:
ðŸ‘‰ In one app, I built cascading dropdowns for Country â†’ State â†’ City, making data entry faster and more accurate.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

7. Explain the concept of Delgations in Power Apps?

EXPLAIN IN ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ Delegation means pushing data operations to the data source instead of the powewr apps, so the app can handle large datasets efficiently.
ðŸ‘‰ This is especially important When working with large datasets â€” for example, SharePoint lists with thousands of records.
ðŸ‘‰ By default, Power Apps limit only pulls 500 records (Which can be increase upto max 2000 records).
ðŸ‘‰ So using without delegation, only those limited records are retrieved, Which can lead to incomplete or missing data.
To slove this, 
ðŸ‘‰ I always use delegable functions like Filter, Sort, and StartsWith, and it return accurate results efficiently. 
ðŸ”¹ This improved both accuracy and performance.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

8. Validations in Power Apps?

EXPLAIN IN ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ðŸ‘‰ Validations are checking the user inputs to make sure the entered data must be in the correct or complete in the expected format, before submitting a form.
From my experience:
ðŸ”¹ I use required field checks (IsBlank) to make sure important fields are not empty.
ðŸ”¹ I apply pattern validations using functions like IsMatch() â€” for example, validating email or phone number formats.
ðŸ”¹ I also use conditional visibility â€” like changing border colors or showing warnings based on input.

Example:
ðŸ‘‰ In one app, I built a registration form where I validated email format, mandatory fields, and showed custom error messages to guide users before submission.
